<DOC><DOCNO> AP890906-0157 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1603EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-US-Burma     09-06 0110</FIRST><SECOND>AM-US-Burma,110</SECOND><UNK>Many Burmese Dissidents Arrested, Some Tortured, U.S. Says</UNK><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Thousands of Burmese opposed to the governmenthave been arrested over the past seven weeks and some are believedto have been tortured in detention, the State Department saidWednesday.   ``The United States government condemns these acts ofoppression,'' department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said.   ``We hope the Burmese government will take immediate steps to endthe torture of those under detention and release all politicalprisoners.''   The arrests began July 20, just before the start ofcommemorations of last year's pro-democracy demonstrations. Theprotests were forcefully suppressed, and about 3,000 Burmese arebelieved to have died.</TEXT></DOC>